0442\u0438\u043d: \u0427\u0435\u043c \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0445\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438|publisher=\u0421\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0430|date=2020-01-16|accessdate=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175\">\nFile:Yury Dud in Nizhnekamsk.jpg|{{center|'''[[Yury Dud]]'''}}\nFile:Sergey Kirienko (01113353) (9776894576) (cropped).jpg|{{center|Kremlin First Deputy Chief of Staff<br />'''[[Sergey Kiriyenko]]'''}}\nFile:14-03-2020 Alexei Kudrin.png|{{center|[[Accounts Chamber of Russia#Chairmen|Accounts Chamber Chairman]]<br />'''[[Alexei Kudrin]]'''}}\nFile:Mikhail Mishustin (2018).jpg|{{center|[[Prime Minister of Russia|Prime Minister]]<br />'''[[Mikhail Mishustin]]'''}}\n</gallery>\n\n==Declined to be candidates==\nThe individuals in this section have publicly denied interest in running.\n\n===United Russia===\n*[[Ramzan Kadyrov]], [[Head of the Chechen Republic|Head of Chechnya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2018/12/22/n_12448873.shtml |title=\u041a\u0430\u0434\u044b\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b, \u0445\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0438 \u0431\u044b\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c |publisher=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430.ru |date=2018-12-22 |accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Yabloko ===\n*[[Grigory Yavlinsky]], former Deputy of the [[State Duma]], former leader of the [[Yabloko]] party, presidential candidate in 1996, 2000 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://echo.msk.ru/news/2553873-echo.html|title=\u042f\u0432\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0435 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 2024 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|publisher=Echo of Moscow|accessdate=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n\n===Independent===\n*[[Maxim Galkin]], comedian and television presenter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ura.news/news/1052409413|title=\u0413\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438.\u043e|publisher=URA.RU|date=2019-11-30|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|group=a}}\n{{reflist|group=b}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Russian elections}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russian presidential election, 2024}}\n[[Category:Presidential elections in Russia|2024]]\n[[Category:2024 elections in Europe]]\n[[Category:2024 in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2024 Russian presidential election\n| country = Russia\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = yes <!-- PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THIS UNTIL 2024 -->\n| previous_election = 2018 Russian presidential election\n| previous_year = 2018\n| election_date = 17 March 2024 (1st round)\n| next_election = 2030 Russian presidential election\n| next_year = 2030\n| opinion_polls = Opinion polling for the 2024 Russian presidential election\n| turnout = \n| registered = 110,564,632 (January 2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cikrf.ru/izbiratel/quantity/20200101.php|title=\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043e \u0447\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0445 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0438\u0437\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439, \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0438\u044e \u043d\u0430 1 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2020 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|publisher=Cikrf.ru |date=2020-01-01 |accessdate=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n| image1 = \n| nominee1 = \n| party1 = \n| home_state1 = \n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n| image2 = \n| nominee2 = \n| party2 = \n| home_state2 = \n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n| image3 = \n| nominee3 = \n| party3 = \n| home_state3 = \n| popular_vote3 = \n| percentage3 = \n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Vladimir Putin]]\n| before_party = Independent politician\n| after_election = \n| after_party = \n}}\nThe '''2024 Russian presidential election''' will take place in March 2024. In accordance with electoral law, the first round will be held on Sunday 17 March 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_40445/c3b8b1b1845f4b4bcb6bfc2a1514d8cc0baccc74/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442 10.01.2003 N 19-\u0424\u0417 (\u0440\u0435\u0434. \u043e\u0442 05.12.2017) \"\u041e \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\" \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f 5. \u041d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|website=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u041f\u043b\u044e\u0441|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> If in the first round no candidate attains an absolute majority of the votes (more than half), then according to the law a second round will take place exactly three weeks later on 7 April 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_40445/a90a2145a34de6130bfb4367daec059ac75a9614/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442 10.01.2003 N 19-\u0424\u0417 (\u0440\u0435\u0434. \u043e\u0442 05.12.2017) \"\u041e \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\" \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f 77. \u041f\u043e\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|website=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u041f\u043b\u044e\u0441|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe term limit established by Article 81 of the Russian Constitution prevents incumbent president [[Vladimir Putin]] from being elected to a new term. The 2024 election will determine the fifth [[President of Russia]]. The winner of the election is scheduled to be [[Russian presidential inauguration|inaugurated]] on 7 May 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_40445/041abf1209079a3f6e2d0e19bca00375bfed931e/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442 10.01.2003 N 19-\u0424\u0417 (\u0440\u0435\u0434. \u043e\u0442 05.12.2017) \"\u041e \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\" \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f 82. \u0412\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===Ineligibility of Vladimir Putin===\n[[File:Vladimir Putin 2019-04-12.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Vladimir Putin]], the incumbent president, whose second term expires on May 7, 2024]]\n\nAccording to point 3 of article 81 of the [[Constitution of Russia]], the same person cannot hold a position of the [[President of the Russian Federation]] more than two terms in a row.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constitution.ru/en/10003000-05.htm |title=Constitution of Russia. Chapter 4. The President of the Russian Federation. Article 81 |publisher=Constitution.ru |date= |accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref> This means that [[Vladimir Putin]], who was elected president in [[2012 Russian presidential election|2012]] and re-elected in [[2018 Russian presidential election|2018]], will not be able to participate in the 2024 presidential election, although some experts suggest that Putin may remain in power after 2024.<ref>{{cite web|author=All RFE/RL sites |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/putin-2024-election-raises-curtain-on-clouded-future/29107186.html |title=Putin's 2024 Problem: Election Win Raises Curtain On Clouded Future |publisher=Rferl.org |date=2018-03-18 |accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref> Putin denied the possibility of his participation in the 2030 election when answering this question of a journalist on 18 March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20180318/1516701655.html|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441 \u043e \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u043c \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445-2030|date=2018-03-18|website=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|language=ru|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> On 25 May 2018, answering a journalist's question during the [[St. Petersburg International Economic Forum|SPIEF]], Putin said that he was not going to hold the post of president for more than two consecutive terms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3641992|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d \u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0443\u0445 \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0434|publisher=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442|date= |accessdate=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\n====\"2024 problem\"====\nThe \"2024 problem\"<ref>\u0420\u0443\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 The New Times [https://newtimes.ru/rubrics/detail/175832/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430 2024] \u0438 [https://newtimes.ru/rubrics/detail/175832/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430-2024]</ref> is connected with end of Putin\u2019s presidential powers in 2024.<ref name=\"fedorov\">{{cite book|editor-last=\u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432|editor-first=\u0412. \u0412. |others=\u0412. \u0412. \u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432, \u042e. \u041c. \u0411\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u041b. \u0413. \u0411\u044b\u0437\u043e\u0432, \u041e. \u041b. \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0437\u0443\u0431, \u041c. \u0412. \u041c\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0418. \u0412. \u0413\u0430\u0432\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432, \u041c. \u0410. \u0412\u044f\u0434\u0440\u043e|title=\u0412\u042b\u0411\u041e\u0420\u042b \u041d\u0410 \u0424\u041e\u041d\u0415 \u041a\u0420\u042b\u041c\u0410: \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b 2016\u20142018 \u0433\u0433. \u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0437\u0438\u0442\u0430|publisher=\u0412\u0426\u0418\u041e\u041c|date=2018|isbn=9785041523244}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Gallup International opinion poll conducted in December 2017, if Putin was not to be on the ballot, 46% would not have known for whom to vote and 19% would have made the ballot paper invalid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dp.ru/a/2017/12/20/Gallup_bez_uchastija_Vladi|title=Gallup: \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u044b \u0440\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f|website=www.dp.ru}}</ref> Valery Fedorov<ref>Director of [[Russian Public Opinion Research Center]]</ref> said that the Russian population does not think about this problem,<ref>{{cite web |author=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 |url=https://www.mk.ru/politics/2019/03/14/konec-epokhi-putina-kak-eto-budet.html |title= \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446 \u044d\u043f\u043e\u0445\u0438 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u043a\u0430\u043a \u044d\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 ''\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u043f\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0439 \u0441\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'' |language=ru |website=|publisher=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0446\u00bb |date=2019-03-14 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> while the focus group participants gathered by the [[Levada Center]] identified two main scenarios for its solution: preservation of presidential powers by Vladimir Putin and the appointment of a successor.<ref name=\"volkov\">{{cite web |author=\u0414\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432 |url=https://www.rbc.ru/newspaper/2019/05/15/5cda6f089a794770fbfb5ec9 |title=\u0427\u0442\u043e \u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435-2024 |language=ru |website=rbc.ru |publisher= |date=2019-05-14 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Ekaterina Schulmann]], a wide elite pact is being sought, the alternative to which is the war of all against all.<ref>{{cite web |author=\u0415\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0428\u0443\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0430\u043d |url=https://www.inliberty.ru/article/shulman/ |title=\u041f\u044f\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a |language=ru |website=inliberty.ru |publisher= |date=2018-03-18 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> According to Oleg Chernozub, the Russian elite is able to find ways to solve this problem,<ref name=\"fedorov\"/> for example, [[Valery Zorkin]] proposed changing the constitution,<ref>{{cite web |author=Anastasia Stognei |url=https://thebell.io/en/russian-political-veteran-suggests-constitutional-tweaks-to-solve-putin-s-2024-problem/ |title=Proposed constitutional changes reveal Kremlin splits over Putin\u2019s \u20182024 problem\u2019 |language=en |website=thebell.io |publisher= |date=2018-10-12 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> [[Vyacheslav Volodin]] proposed expanding the powers of the parliament.<ref>{{cite web |author=Peter Mironenko |url=https://thebell.io/en/the-russian-elite-is-jostling-to-solve-putin-s-2024-problem/ |title=The Russian elite is jostling to solve Putin\u2019s \u20182024 problem\u2019 |language=en |website=thebell.io |publisher= |date=2019-07-20 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn general, there are several scenarios for the development of events in the political field of Russia in 2024:<ref name=\"gulf\">{{cite web |author=Andrew Hammond |url=https://gulfnews.com/opinion/op-eds/putin-win-will-put-politics-in-flux-1.2182488 |title=Putin win will put politics in flux |language=en |website=gulfnews.com |publisher= |date=2018-03-04 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n* '''Competitive free elections'''\n*: One of the least likely scenarios is that the next president after Putin will be determined as a result of an open political process.<ref name=\"gulf\"/>\n* '''Assignment of a successor'''<ref name=\"politek4\">{{cite web |author=\u0422\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0447\u0443\u043a, \u0412\u044f\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u043a\u043e, \u0410\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0434 \u0425\u0430\u0447\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432 |url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2018/03/30/76001-problema-2024-ili-politekonomiya-chetvertogo-sroka |title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430-2024, \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430 |language=ru |website=novayagazeta.ru |publisher= |date=2018-03-30 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n*: One of the most likely scenarios is when [[Vladimir Putin]] will appoint his successor, who will be the main candidate for the 2024 election.<ref name=\"fedorov\" /> Putin himself was successor of [[Boris Yeltsin]], and then [[Dmitry Medvedev]] was Putin's successor for one term.<ref name=\"gulf\" /> Participants of focus groups, among Putin's possible successors, often name [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Sergey Shoygu]], less often [[Sergey Lavrov]], [[Sergey Sobyanin]], or even [[Pavel Grudinin]]; many say that he will be an unknown, \"fresh\" person.<ref name=\"volkov\"/> Political analyst Azhdar Kurtov believes that to ensure the victory of a successor in the elections, there may be recognition of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] and [[Luhansk People's Republic]] independence.<ref>{{cite web |author=\u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 |url=https://svpressa.ru/politic/article/231347/ |title=\u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0414\u041d\u0420 \u0438 \u041b\u041d\u0420 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0438 2024 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 |language=ru |website=svpressa.ru |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n*: In connection with the alleged transit of power, questions arise - will a successor be able to protect Putin in the same way that Putin protected Yeltsin? Will it be possible to change the president without serious destabilization and internal struggle? And most importantly - can the system built by Putin function without Putin?<ref>{{cite book|first=Tony|last=Wood |title=Russia Without Putin: Money, Power and the Myths of the New Cold War |publisher=Verso Books |date=2018 |pages=174\u2013175/224  |isbn=1788731263 |ref= }}</ref>\n* '''Amendment of the Constitution'''<ref name=\"politek4\" />\n*: Another possible way for Putin to retain power after 2024 called a possible amendment to the  [[Constitution of Russia|Constitution]], removing the limitation of the terms of presidency in order for Putin to run for president in 2024. However, Putin said he was not going to change the Constitution in an interview with [[Megyn Kelly]] in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20180310/1516070848.html|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044e|date=2018-03-10|website=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|language=ru|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref>\n*: A scenario in which restrictions that prevent Putin from remaining as president of the Russian Federation will be lifted.<ref name=\"gulf\" /> [[Sergey Alexandrovich Markov|Sergei Markov]] says that Putin\u2019s repeated statements that there will be no abolition of terms of office have led discussion of possible scenarios for 2024 to a standstill.<ref name=\"bloomber\">{{cite web |author=Ilya Arkhipov  & Henry Meyer |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-12/putin-seeks-to-lock-in-parliament-control-amid-falling-ratings |title=Putin Seeks to Lock in Parliament Control |language=en |website=bloomberg.com |publisher= |date=2019-07-12 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> Even a closer union with [[Belarus]] is being discussed.<ref name=\"kreml\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.19rus.info/index.php/vlast-i-politika/item/99220-kreml-produmal-neskolko-stsenariev-chtoby-putin-eshche-dolgo-ostavalsya-u-vlasti |title=\u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u044c \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u043b \u043d\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0441\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0432, \u0447\u0442\u043e\u0431\u044b \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0435\u0449\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u0443 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 |language=ru |website=19rus.info |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n* '''Putin retains power, but not as president'''\n*: Putin may take another position in 2024 (as it was from 2008 to 2012) and again run for president in 2030. On 23 March 2018, Presidential Press Secretary [[Dmitry Peskov]] said that Putin is not going to change the Constitution and if there will be any constitutional reform, it will not concern presidential powers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20180323/1517079765.html|title=\u0412 \u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044f|date=2018-03-23|website=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|language=ru|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rg.ru/2018/03/23/peskov-putin-ne-nameren-meniat-pod-sebia-konstituciiu.html|title=\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0441\u0435\u0431\u044f \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044e|website=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430|language=ru|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref>\n*: As an option, Putin can choose the posts of the [[List of heads of government of Russia|Prime Minister]]<ref name=\"wegren\">{{cite book|first=Stephen K.|last= Wegren |title=Putin's Russia: Past Imperfect, Future Uncertain |url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1538114275 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |date=2018 |page=2/360 |isbn=1538114275 |ref= }}</ref> with extended powers<ref name=\"bloomber\"/><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://newtimes.ru/articles/detail/182816/ |title=Bloomberg \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u043e \u0440\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0435 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0445\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0443 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 |language=ru |website=newtimes.ru |publisher= |date=2019-07-12 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> or the [[Chairman of the State Duma]].<ref name=\"gulf\" /> This option involves expanding the powers of parliament.<ref name=\"bloomber\" /> Political scientists are also discussing the possibility of transferring powers to the [[Security Council of Russia|Security Council]] or the [[State Council (Russia)|State Council]] of the Russian Federation.<ref name=\"kreml\"/> In January 2020, Putin announced plans to amend the Constitution and expand the powers of the Duma and State Council. This has led to further speculation that he may seek to lead a strengthened State Council after leaving the office of president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/world/putin-outlines-sweeping-powers-for-state-council-in-shakeup|title=Vladimir Putin outlines sweeping powers for state council in Russian government shakeup|publisher=National Post|date=20 January 2020}}</ref> It is also possible that Putin will retain political power without taking a formal position.<ref name=\"wegren\"/>\n\nAccording to political analyst Kirill Rogov, the constitutional design of Russian statehood remains unclear due to the unsuccessful experience of the \u201ctandem\u201d and the lack of institutions of distributed power.<ref>{{cite web |author=\u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0432 |url=https://www.inliberty.ru/article/shulman/ |title=\u041f\u044f\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a |language=ru |website=inliberty.ru |publisher= |date=2018-03-18 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>  In addition to the obvious conflict between [[Putinism|Putin\u2019s political regime]] and the [[Politics of Russia|official state system]], the problem is also the impossibility for Putin to guarantee security for himself and his family if he leaves office completely. However, poor health may encourage him to leave.<ref name=\"dilemma\">{{cite web |author= |url=https://newtimes.ru/articles/detail/177294/ |title=\u0414\u0438\u043b\u0435\u043c\u043c\u0430 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u0443\u0439\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0437\u044f \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f |language=ru |website= |publisher= |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\n===2020 constitutional reform===\n{{main|2020 amendments to the Constitution of Russia}}\nDuring his [[2020 Presidential Address to the Federal Assembly|annual address to the Federal Assembly]] on 15 January 2020, Putin proposed a constitutional amendments. According to assumptions, this reform will help him maintain influence on the government even after leaving the post of President.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://newizv.ru/news/politics/13-02-2020/konstitutsiya-kakie-popravki-odobril-putin?|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044f: \u043a\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u043e\u0434\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043b \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d|language=ru |website= |publisher=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f |date=2020-02-13 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.mk.ru/social/2020/01/31/polovina-rossiyan-uvidela-v-izmenenii-konstitucii-zhelanie-putina-sokhranit-vlast.html|title=\u041f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f\u043d \u0443\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0432 \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0445\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c|language=ru |website= |publisher=\u041c\u041a.RU |date=2020-01-31 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nA number of amendments affect the presidential authority:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sozd.duma.gov.ru/bill/885214-7|title=\u2116885214-7 \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442 :: \u0421\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u044f\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|website=sozd.duma.gov.ru|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n*Putin proposed to partially weaken the President, and the [[State Duma]] has the right to approve members of the government (with the exception of power Ministers, whose appointment will be under the jurisdiction of the [[Federation Council (Russia)|Federation Council]]). \n*Remove the words \"in a row\" from the article about the maximum number of terms a President (that means that in the future presidents can serve two terms max for life, Putin can't run for President in all subsequent elections, and Dmitry Medvedev will be able to run just once, as previously already served one term as President).\n*Putin proposed to state the role of the [[State Council (Russia)|State Council]] in the Constitution. However, the Constitution will only state that the State Council is formed by the President, as well as the goals of its formation. The main powers of this body are proposed to be documented in an ordinary Federal Law (in March of the same year, Putin said that he was not going to head the state Council after leaving the post of President. In his opinion, such a decision would lead to dual power, which would be disastrous for Russia).<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.mk.ru/politics/2020/03/06/vladimir-putin-obyasnil-pochemu-ne-vozglavit-gossovet.html|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043b, \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u043d\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442|language=ru |website= |publisher=\u041c\u041a.RU |date=2020-03-06 |accessdate=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n*The amendments will also set stricter requirements for people running for president. Namely, they will have to have lived in Russia for the last 25 years (according to the old norm of 10 years), and the President can not become a person who has or ever had a foreign citizenship or residence permit in another country, while people who previously had citizenship of a country that or part of which became part of Russia will be able to run for president (this means that former Ukrainian citizens who lived in Crimea in 2014 and received Russian citizenship after the annexation of the peninsula will be able to run for president in the future, however, if under the old rule they could run already in these elections. Now they will not be able to do this until 2039).\n*Also, after the amendments, all former presidents will receive the status of senators for life, at the same time, they will have the right to refuse this status.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2020/02/11/822786-bivshie-prezidenti-status-senatorov|title=\u0411\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0441\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430|language=ru |website= |publisher=\u0412\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 |date=2020-02-11 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nIn order to adopt these amendments, Putin proposed holding a [[2020 Russian constitutional referendum|popular vote]], in accordance with the results of which the amendments will enter into force or be rejected.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://tass.com/politics/1119835|title=Constitutional amendments should enter into force only after nationwide vote, says Putin|language=en |website= |publisher=TASS |date=2020-02-13 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Individuals who have publicly expressed interest==\nIndividuals in this section have expressed an interest in running for president.\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break}}\n\n===United Russia===\n*[[Maxim Oreshkin]], former [[Ministry of Economic Development (Russia)|Minister of Economic Development]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2019/03/04/n_12706609.shtml|title=\u041e\u0440\u0435\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d \u0445\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043b \u0431\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c |publisher=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430.ru |date=2018-03-04 |accessdate=2018-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ru/mnenie/glava-mera-riskuet-pervym/|title=\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0440\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u043c|publisher=News.ru |date=2018-03-04 |accessdate=2018-03-04}}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175\">\nFile:Maxim Oreshkin (11 December 2017).jpg|{{center|former [[Ministry of Economic Development (Russia)|Minister]]<br />'''[[Maxim Oreshkin]]'''}}\n</gallery>\n\n===Communist Party===\n*[[Pavel Grudinin]]{{refn|group=a|name=Grudinin|Pavel Grudinin is not a member of the Communist party, but expressed his intention to run for this party.}}, CEO of the Lenin State Farm, former Deputy of the [[Moscow Oblast Duma]], 2018 presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailystorm.ru/news/grudini-obyavil-chto-budet-ballotirovatsya-v-prezidenty-v-2024-godu|title=\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0431\u0430\u043b\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b \u0432 2024 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443|publisher=Daily Storm|date=2019-11-14|accessdate=2019-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://fedpress.ru/news/50/policy/2366138|title=\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430|publisher=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441|date=2019-11-14|accessdate=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n*[[Nikolay Platoshkin]]{{refn|group=a|name=Platoshkin|Nikolai Platoshkin is not a member of the Communist party, but he ran for the State Duma in 2019 from this party and has encouraged further cooperation with the party.}}, politologist, public activist, leader of the movement \"For a New Socialism\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://echo.msk.ru/blog/v_radionov/2536761-echo/|title=\u041b\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0434 \u0413\u043e\u0437\u043c\u0430\u043d \u2013 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u044e \u041f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0443: \u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0443\u0442 \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u2014 \u044d\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0438 \u0432\u0430\u0448\u0430 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430!|publisher=Echo of Moscow|date= |accessdate=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175\">\nFile:Pavel Grudinin (cropped, 2018-03-19).jpg|{{center|CEO of the Lenin State Farm<br />'''[[Pavel Grudinin]]'''{{refn|group=a|name=Grudinin}}}}\n</gallery>\n\n===Liberal Democratic Party===\n*[[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], Deputy of the [[State Duma]], leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia|Liberal Democratic Party]], presidential candidate in 1991, 1996, 2000, 2008, 2012 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://regnum.ru/news/2393969.html |title=\u041d\u0435 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044e \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0447\u0438\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f: \u0416\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u043e \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u043c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0449\u0435\u043c |publisher=Regnum.ru |date=2015-11-26 |accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mk.ru/politics/2018/03/21/zhirinovskiy-oproverg-slukhi-o-neuchastii-v-vyborakh2024-ne-dozhdetes.html |title=\u0416\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0433 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0445\u0438 \u043e \u043d\u0435\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445-2024: \"\u041d\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0441\u044c\" |publisher=Mk.ru |date= |accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175\">\nFile:Vladimir Zhirinovsky 2015-06-29.jpg|{{center|[[State Duma|Deputy]]<br />'''[[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]]'''}}\n</gallery>\n\n===A Just Russia===\n*[[Oleg Bryachak]], Deputy of the [[Pskov]] City Duma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://informpskov.ru/news/279698.html|title=\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u0411\u0440\u044f\u0447\u0430\u043a \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u043e \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0432\u043e\u044e \u043a